[1
Date: Tue 20 Nov 2001
From: Dr Carol Shoshkes Reiss <carol.reiss@nyu.edu> [edited

Protection from Disease versus Susceptibility to Infection
----------------------------------------------------------
I think it is very important to distinguish between protection from disease
versus susceptibility to infection. The ability to be infected will be
essentially inversely correlated with the presence of circulating and
pulmonary neutralizing antibody. It is highly likely that those of us who
were vaccinated have very diminished titers of antibody. However, vaccinia
virus-specific T cells are the critical component of recovery, and
previously vaccinated adults are replete with circulating memory T cells
which will rapidly expand and eliminate smallpox [_Variola virus_.
Therefore, it is very unlikely that disease will be manifest. An increase
in serum antibody titer shortly after inapparent infection is what I predict.
Another point. A friend (Solomon L. Mowshowitz, PhD) made this suggestion.
If there is a limited vaccine supply, within days of scarifying one member
of a family, the virus could be harvested from the site and transferred to
others, sequentially. The caveats about transmissible infectious diseases
(for instance HCV, HBV) are a concern, and of course no immunocompromised
individual should receive the vaccine.
--
Carol Shoshkes Reiss, PhD
Biology dept NYU
Editor, Viral Immunology
<carol.reiss@nyu.edu>
