Date: Tue 20 Nov 2001
From: Prof. Dr. M. Dietrich <dietrich@bni.uni-hamburg.de> [edited

A Comment on Risk
-----------------
It should be considered that smallpox vaccination in adults not
[previously vaccinated may result in severe complications. According to
previous experience PVE [postvaccinial encephalitis may occur in 1:10 000
for ages 1-3 years,1:650 for ages 4-5 years, and 1:120 for ages 11-14 years.
Therefore attenuated strains [of vaccinia virus, as for instance P
(Posthuma) D (Dekking) N (van der Noordaa) vaccine, possibly under the
protection of specific anti-vaccinial immunoglobulin, should be preferred.
(Vide: Regamey R.H. Rev Intern.des Services de Sante 1965,38,269; Kempe
C.H. WHO Bulletin 1961,25,71).
--
M.Dietrich
B-Nocht Inst. Clinical Department
B.Nocht str.74
20359 Hamburg
Germany
<dietrich@bni.uni-hamburg.de>
